There are obviously a lot of non-Jews who want to learn more about this religion. Some people come to Temple for non-dental service. But that did not stop me from thinking an article like this would be less controversial than the recent piece by Sara Boboltz which highlights the fact that synagogues are easily mistaken for restaurants. Could you imagine if 60 Minutes started by lavishing praise all over the Supreme Court, building a case that Jews are just like everyone else and celebrating the way the Court appreciates a good dish of broccoli and beef?

As my temporary smorgasbording buddies answered the questionnaire, I asked, “Would you be disgusted if I had brought a cake with other people's names on it?”

“Oh no, she's good,” they replied, bending the rules.

“It's probably five stars and timely,” said the octogenarian who confirmed she was Jewish but said she wanted to read more.

Then there was “Alice”. She came in five minutes before the service and put one cream puff in her mouth, threw the box onto the unconverted couch soldiered with her to the side of the room, poured a beverage, and positioned herself at a table, clearly equipped for electronic to-dos.
